snippet.textDisplay:
I've done a similar thing with a friend a few times, but along with finding out where I am (not to the level of detail that you do in this vid) I have to make my own way home!

This is a fucking cool series - get to show off bits of the UK that most people would never get to see or even hear of. Who the fuck would ever go to that place in Swindon unless you live there? (Not meant as an insult - I live in a similar area). Appreciate it's already been filmed, but you should make your final guess in a local pub with a pint of the local bitter - maybe have a chat with a local geezer and show off the local accent or something if people were up for it.

Also, this kind of proves my theory that you really can't get fully lost for very long in the UK...

snippet.textDisplay: Car number plates would be good to use. They usually have a garage name on the number plate, usually with a postcode or area. Also, the cars origin is identified by the first letter of the number plate, so if it begins with A, it’s Anglia, B is Birmingham, C is Wales, D is Deeside, E is Essex, F is Forest and Fens, G is Guildford, H is Hampshire etc so if you see a lot of number plates beginning with E, you know it’s likely Essex

snippet.textDisplay:
As someone who has been to Kilve a lot this was rather painful to watch, what with his pronunciation of Kilve (it's not Kilv-a it's simply Kilv), then when it said Kilve many times and he was more focussed on it being near Bath and Bristol, I felt like screaming that he had the answer within the first couple minutes of him being there


*For anyone who doesn't know, Kilve is a little seaside town on the Bristol coast, it's mostly known for its rock pools as the beach is much more a stoney beach than a sandy one, and you're more likely to find dog walkers than tourists. It's also a rather nice place to go for campfires / bonfires as at nighttime you're not likely to get bombarded like other beaches


It's also often used as a residential place for school kids, I myself didn't go but my brother did when he was in year 6
